people" in all their diversity. Today the university is refortifying its commitment to the defense of the status quo off campus and the regulation of students, faculty, and staff on campus. The progressive forms of knowledge that the student-led movements demanded and helped to produce are being attacked on every front. Not only is this a reactionary move against the social advances since the '60s and '70s-it is part of the larger threat of anti-intellectualism in the United States.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aRiotszMichiganzDetroit. 4a20th century protest. 4aamerican studies. 4acampus activism. 4acollege student. 4aethnic studies. 4ahuman rights advocate. 4aimmigration. 4aindigenous people. 4aintellectual landscape. 4apoly sci student. 4asocial movement. 4astudent body leader. 4asuccessful social movements. 4awomens rights. 4awomens studies. 70(DE-601)1041974120(DE-588)4058171-8aStudentenbewegung2gnd 70(DE-601)1061345580(DE-588)4061778-6aUniversität2gnd 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520966284423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520966284.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066755-4  UC Press eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles